column1: Metadata:
[1] [Observations] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater is negligible.
[2] [Methodology] | Data collected from national reports/survey/statistics/international surveys, etc..
[3] [Methodology] | Treated municipal wastewater discharged (secondary water) calculated by subtracting direct use of treated municipal wastewater from treated municipal wastewater
[4] [Components] | This is groundwater coming from Saudi Arabia, but it is mostly brackish.

[5] [Comparability (over time)] | 19.25 km3 for rainfallequals62mm in Mitchell,T.D.et al.2003. A comprehensive set of high-resolution grids of monthly climate for Europe and the globe: the observed record (1901-2000) and 16 scenarios (2001-2100)->average of 125 mm/y(1961-90)
[6] [Adjustment] | One source mentions that 80% of the rainfall evaporates, leaving 20% as IRWR.
[7] [Observations] | Domestic wastewater produced outside urban areas might have also been considered
[8] [Methodology] | Data collected from national reports/survey/statistics/international surveys, etc..
[9] [Overall accuracy] | Abu Sukar,H.K.et al.2007. Agro-hydro-meteorological data book for the State of Qatar->average (1972-2005) 80.2 mm/y. IPCC 1961-90->74 mm
[10] [Observations] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater is negligible.
[11] [Components] | From Saudi Arabia
[12] [Overall accuracy] | From national consultant (Yousef Al-Dakheel): Volume is 245.5 km3/year, which is equal to 114 mm/year. FAO, 1997, gave 59 mm/year.
[13] [Adjustment] | 1.0 recharges the "usable" aquifers.

[14] [Adjustment] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater, estimated by J. Margat, is nearly 100% of groundwater recharge; It is an arid country; surface water is mostly flood water it infiltrates into the aquifers.
[15] [Components] | To Kuwait 0.02; to Bahrain 0.112; to Qatar 0.002; to Jordan 0.18; to Iraq 0.08 (Umm er Radhuma).
[16] [Observations] | Minimum requirment for un ristricted irrigation is advanced secondarz treatment.

[17] [Overall accuracy] | Total IRWR=6.859 (Surface water 3.248 and groundwater 3.611). However, in order to take into consideration an overlap (it was decided to keep the same overlap 1.4) 0.7 was added to both surface water and groundwater.

[18] [Components] | Total outflow = IRWR->6.86 (Araks 5.62; Agstay 0.35 (to Azerbaijan); Debet 0.89 (to Georgia))Total outflow from Armenia to Araks border river 3.80 (Sevdjur 1.05; Razdam 0.70; Azat 0.19; Vedi 0.06; Arpa 0.69; Megri 0.09; Vokchi 0.33; Vorotan 0.69)
[19] [Adjustment] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater is less than 100%; not all the groundwater is drained by the rivers.

[20] [Components] | From Georgia 11.91; from Armenia 5.97 (Araks 5.62 + Agstay 0.35); from the Islamic Republic of Iran 7.50 - 5.97 (Araks, but removing 5.97 that already entered from Armenia to avoid double-counting ).
[21] [Components] | Surface water produced internally: Caspian Sea basin: 14.4; Black Sea basin: 42.5.

[22] [Adjustment] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater (GW) is less than 100% of GW recharge; most of the GW is drained by the rivers (equivalent to the low flow of water courses). Some groundwater escapes and flows out into the sea.
[23] [Components] | Inflow not submitted to treaty: Mktvari 0.91; Potskhovi 0.25; Debet 0.89
[24] [Adjustment] | Half of the flow. Agreement with Turkey in 1925 to have each half of the flow of the Corub river, which originates in Georgia
[25] [Components] | From Turkey 4.31 (0.91 through Mktvari, 0.25 through Potskhovi, and 3.15 through Corub/Choroki as agreed with Turkey); from Armenia 0.89 (Debet)
[26] [Components] | Outflow all to Azerbaijan (11.91): Kura 8.23; Iori 0.58; Alazani 3.1
[27] [Adjustment] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater is estimated to be around 40% of the groundwater recharge as some groundwater flows directly into the sea.

[28] [Components] | Helmand from Afghanistan 6.7; Hari Rod (Tedzhen) from Afghanistan 1.07 (in fact becomes border, but because of treaty between the Islamic Republic of Iran and Turkmenistan considered to be incoming).

[29] [Components] | An agreement existed with Afghanistan to use 26 m3/s (or 0.82 km3/yr) of the Helmand river, which ceased however with the Taliban regime; an agreement exists with Turkmenistan on Harid Rod, allocating 0.75 to Turkmenistan, leaving 0.32 for the Islamic Republic of Iran.
[30] [Adjustment] | 50% of flow
[31] [Components] | Araks to Azerbaijan 7.5; affluents of Tigris to Iraq 10; Hari/Rod-Tedzhen to Turkmenistan 1.07; Atrek to Turkmenistan 0.1.

[32] [Components] | Araks to Azerbaijan 7.5; affluents of Tigris to Iraq 10. There is also an outflow to Iraq of 24.7 by the Karun. However, this river flows into the Shatt Al Arab just beofre reaching the sea and is therefore of no use to Iraq and thus not counted.
[33] [Components] | Tedzhen to Turkmenistan 1.07; Atrek to Turkmenistan 0.1.
[34] [Components] | Tedzhen to Turkmenistan 0.75; Atrek to Turkmenistan 0.04.
[35] [Components] | From the Islamic Republic of Iran 10 (Tigris tributaries); from Turkey 21.33 (Tigris); from the Syrian Arab Republic 30 (Euphrates, actual 9).
[36] [Observations] | This is the water amount from the unilateral agreement from TUR, subsequently split between IRQ/SYR 58%/42%
[37] [Adjustment] | Karun 24.7 joins the Shatt Al-Arab on the border and cannot be considered as a resource, since it enters Iraq just before flowing into the sea
[38] [Components] | From Saudi Arabia 0.08 (groundwater from Umm er Radhuma)
[39] [Observations] | The overlap between surface water and groundwater is negligible.
[40] [Components] | From Lebanon 0.16 (of which 0.138 from Hasbani); from the Syrian Arab Republic 0.125 (Golan); from West Bank 0.02
[41] [Components] | To Gaza 0.015
[42] [Components] | From the Syrian Arab Republic (into Dan spring) 0.25; from West Bank 0.325; from Lebanon 0.150 (Hulah Lake)
[43] [Components] | To Gaza 0.025
[44] [Methodology] | Estimate by the ministry
[45] [Methodology] | Not treated municipal wastewater = Produced  municipal Wastewater - Treated Municipal Wastewater
[46] [Methodology] | Treated municipal wastewater discharged (secondary water) calculated by subtracting direct use of treated municipal wastewater from treated municipal wastewater
[47] [Reference Area] | Average of rainfall from 1937/38 to 2005/06; IPCC (1961-1990) equals 111.

[48] [Adjustment] | Average, calculated based on 0.283 from M.Bilbeisi (1992), 0.474 (0.418-0.530) from Shlami Dinar (NATO 2004), 0.456 from Annual Environment Statistics (1997), and 0.437 from Al Kwaldeh(1997).
[49] [Observations] | Yarmouk: first bordering then entering from the Syrian Arab Republic

[50] [Observations] | From the Syrian Arab Repubic. In 2004 and 2005 the actual inflow was only 0.119 and 0.092 km3 respectively, according to M. Bani Hani, national expert, based on data from MWI and JVA.
[51] [Observations] | Jordan river with Israel. Natural of 0.540 is equal to discharge leaving Lake Kinnereth (BIRD, 1993)
[52] [Components] | Natural inflow from Saudi Arabia from Disi aquifer 0.18; Inflow from Syria 0.09
[53] [Observations] | Actual groundwater inflow from Saudi Arabia is estimated to be 0 due to exploitation of the Saq aquifer in Saudi Arabia.

[54] [Adjustment] | Overlap between surface water and groundwater is groundwater produced internally minus estimated groundwater outflow into the sea(these are mostly the sub-marine springs of Chekka);it is equivalent to the base flow of the rivers.
[55] [Components] | Surface water outflow to the Syrian Arab Republic: 'El-Assi/Orontes 0.415 (actual 0.335); Hasbani to Israel 0.138 including 0.030 from Wazzani. Total to Israel: 0.160
[56] [Adjustment] | Informal agreement between Lebanon and the Syrian Arab Republic leaves 0.080 of El-Assi/Orontos for Lebanon and the rest to the Syrian Arab Republic.
[57] [Components] | Groundwater outflow into Israel 0.150 (Hulah Lake); into the Syrian Arab Republic 0.130 (Dan springs)
[58] [Methodology] | Not treated municipal wastewater = Produced  municipal Wastewater - Treated Municipal Wastewater
[59] [Methodology] | Treated municipal wastewater discharged (secondary water) calculated by subtracting direct use of treated municipal wastewater from treated municipal wastewater
[60] [Adjustment] | Range from 1.485 to 1.671 at the entrance to the Dead Sea, but to count zero since Palestinians have been denied use of the Jordan river.
[61] [Components] | From Israel to Gaza Strip
[62] [Reference Area] | West Bank only but exploitable groundwater in Gaza Strip expected to be very small
[63] [Components] | TO:  Iraq: 9 (Euphrates)

[64] [Components] | Turkey has unilaterally guaranteed to allow 15.75 km3/year (500 m3/s) of water cross the border to the Syrian Arab Republic, but no formal agreement has been obtained so far on the sharing of the Euphrates water. To Georgia (Corub River) 3.15

[65] [Overall accuracy] | Original capacities reported in the Water Report 34 were substantially larger, but these included several small dams that were later to contain substantial units problems that have since been corrected
[66] [Adjustment] | Data might be slightly underestimated
[67] [Components] | Kabul (Indus) 11.5; Helmand 9.3; Hari Rod-Murghab 3.1; Northern 1.9; Amu Darya (Panj) 11.7.
[68] [Components] | Kabul (Indus) 1.92; Helmand and Western 2.98; Northern and Murghab 2.14; Hari-Rod 0.64; Amu Darya (Panj) 2.97.
[69] [Adjustment] | Overlap is considered to be less than 10 percent of the groundwater resources. Afghanistan is an arid country.

[70] [Components] | Indus to PAK 21.5; AD basin (Kunduz and Kokcha) to TKM 11.7; Murghab to TKM 1.25 (total is 3.1, but most is lost in the desert  at the border); Helmand to IRN 6.7; Hari Rod (Tedzhen in TKM) to (border between AFG and) IRN 1.07. Total is less than the TRWR, because a large part evaporates in depressions at or just over the borders with the IRN and TKM and is  therefore not counted as outflow.
[71] [Components] | Helmand to the Islamic Republic of Iran 6.7

[72] [Components] | According to an agreement between the Islamic Republic of Iran and Afghanistan in 1972, the Islamic Republic of Iran can use 26 m3/s of the Helmand river all year round, which is equal to 0.82 km3/year.

[73] [Components] | Syr Darya 3.3 (Ref:UNDP. 2004. Water resources of Kazakhstan in the new millennium.); Balkhash-Alakol 16.4; Chu-Talas-Assa 1.2; Irtysh 24.5; Nura-Sarysu 1.7; Ishim 2.6; Tobol-Torgai 1.5; Ural-Caspian 5.3.

[74] [Observations] | 626 groundwater fields explored with total reserves of 15.93 km3/year; reserves with salinity rate up to 1 g/l are 33.85 km3/year; reserves with salinity rate up to 10 g/l are 57.63 km3/year (Ref: UNDP. 2004.
